          Design Principles ________________|                                |_________________ Design Patterns
Design principles developers ko guide krta hai to write clean,                   Design Pattern = common problems ke liye ready-made solutions (templates),
maintainable, reusable, and scalable code.                                       Ye code nahi hota ❌, Ye solution ka idea / structure hota hai ✅.
                                                                                 Design Pattern ka Purpose,Mostly objects ke creation aur interaction ke liye hi hota hai :
🔹 Types of Design Principles 🔹                                                                                                                                   Object kaise banega.
1️⃣ SOLID Principles(Object-Oriented Focused)                                                                                                                       Objects kaise interact karenge.
  Note:- OOP provides the concepts, while SOLID provides the guidelines to use those concepts effectively.                                                          Structure kaise hoga.
        OOP = Tools (hammer, screwdriver) 🔧.
        SOLID = Rules / Engineering knowledge 🧠.
 🔥 Explanation Of SOLID principles :
               S → Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
               O → Open/Closed Principle (OCP)
               L → Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
               I → Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
               D → Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
     🟢 1. Single Responsibility Principle (SRP) 
               👉 Ek class ka sirf ek hi kaam hona chahiye.
                     ❌ Galat:
                            class UserService {
                             void saveUser() { }
                             void sendEmail() { }
                            }
                     ✅ Sahi:
                            class UserService {
                             void saveUser() { }
                            }

                            class EmailService {
                             void sendEmail() { }
                            }
     🟢 2. Open/Closed Principle (OCP)
               👉 Code open hona chahiye extension ke liye,
                   but closed hona chahiye modification ke liye.
                   Matlab:
                    Existing code ko change na karo ❌
                    Naya feature add karna ho → new class banao ✅
                     ✅ Ex -
                            interface Payment {
                               void pay();
                            }

                            class CreditCardPayment implements Payment {
                                public void pay() { }
                            }

                            class UpiPayment implements Payment {
                                public void pay() { }
                            }
     🟢 3. Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
               👉 Child class ko parent ki jagah use kar sako bina problem ke.
                     ❌ Galat Example (LSP Break) :
                           👉 Parent class me methods define kiye, lekin child unko properly follow nahi kar raha.
                            class Cat {
                                void drinkMilk() {
                                    System.out.println("Cat drinks milk");
                                }

                                void speak() {
                                    System.out.println("Meow");
                                }
                            }

                            class PetCat extends Cat {
                                @Override
                                void drinkMilk() {
                                    System.out.println("Pet cat drinks milk");
                                }

                                @Override
                                void speak() {
                                    System.out.println("Meow Meow");
                                }
                            }

                            class ToyCat extends Cat {
                                @Override
                                void drinkMilk() {
                                    throw new RuntimeException("Toy cat can't drink milk ❌");
                                }

                                @Override
                                void speak() {
                                    throw new RuntimeException("Toy cat can't speak ❌");
                                }
                            }
                                🔴 Problem kya hai?
                                - ToyCat actually real cat nahi hai
                                - Lekin fir bhi Cat ko extend kar raha hai
                                - Parent ke methods ko properly follow nahi kar raha
                                👉 Agar kahin aisa code ho:
                                                     Cat cat = new ToyCat();
                                                     cat.drinkMilk();  // 💥 Runtime error
                                👉 Matlab:
                                        Child ko parent ki jagah use kiya → program toot gaya ❌, LSP violate ho gaya.
     🟢 4. Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)
               👉 Client ko wo methods implement karne ke liye force mat karo jo use nahi chahiye.
                     ❌ Galat:
                            interface Worker {
                                void work();
                                void eat();
                            }

                            class Robot implements Worker {
                                public void work() { }
                                public void eat() { } // useless ❌
                            }
                     ✅ Sahi:
                            interface Workable {
                                void work();
                            }

                            interface Eatable {
                                void eat();
                            }
     🟢 5. Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)
               👉 High-level class low-level class pe depend na kare — dono abstraction pe depend karein.
                     ❌ Galat:
                            class Employee {
                                void work() {
                                    System.out.println("Employee working");
                                }
                            }

                            class CEO {
                                Employee emp = new Employee();  // ❌ direct dependency

                                void manage() {
                                    emp.work();
                                }
                            }
                            🔴 Problem:
                            CEO directly Employee pe depend hai ❌
                            Agar kal Employee change hua → CEO ka code bhi change ❌
                            👉 Tight coupling 😵
                     ✅ Sahi:
                            interface Worker {
                                void work();
                            }

                            class Employee implements Worker {
                                public void work() {
                                    System.out.println("Employee working");
                                }
                            }

                            class Manager implements Worker {
                                public void work() {
                                    System.out.println("Manager managing");
                                }
                            }

                            class CEO {
                                Worker worker;   // ✅ abstraction use

                                CEO(Worker worker) {
                                    this.worker = worker;
                                }

                                void manage() {
                                    worker.work();
                                }
                            }
                            ✅ Solution 
                                👉 CEO ab directly Employee pe depend nahi hai
                                👉 CEO sirf Worker (interface) ko jaanta hai
2️⃣ Other Key Principles :
                 DRY → Don’t Repeat Yourself
                                 - Duplicate code avoid karna
                 KISS → Keep It Simple, Stupid
                                 - Complex solutions avoid karo
                 YAGNI → You Aren’t Gonna Need It
                                 - Sirf jo required ho wahi implement karo
                 Composition over Inheritance
                                 - Class behavior ke liye inheritance ki bajaye composition use karo



🔹 Design Patterns ke Types (3 Main Categories) 🔹

          🟢 1. Creational Design Patterns
                    👉 Object kaise banayein (creation logic)
                               Examples:
                                      Singleton
                                      Factory
                                      Abstract Factory
                                      Builder
                                      Prototype
          🟡 2. Structural Design Patterns
                    👉 Objects ko kaise arrange / structure karein
                               Examples:
                                      Adapter
                                      Decorator
                                      Facade
                                      Proxy
                                      Composite
          🔵 3. Behavioral Design Patterns
                    👉 Objects ka behavior & communication kaise hoga
                               Examples:
                                      Observer
                                      Strategy
                                      Command
                                      State
                                      Iterator


                                                                  🔹 Creational Design Pattern 🔹  

🟢 1. Singleton Pattern
👉 Ek hi object poore application me exist kare.
    Use:
        Database connection
        Logger
        Configuration
Ex-

class DBConnection {

    private static DBConnection instance;
    private Connection connection;

    // Private constructor
    private DBConnection() {
        try {
            String url = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydb";
            String username = "root";
            String password = "password";

            connection = DriverManager.getConnection(url, username, password);
            System.out.println("Database Connected ✅");

        } catch (SQLException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }

    // Singleton method
    public static DBConnection getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            instance = new DBConnection();
        }
        return instance;
    }

    public Connection getConnection() {
        return connection;
    }
}

 🔹 Singleton ke multiple types (implementations)
  1.1 Early Initialization (Eager Loading)
       👉 Object pehle hi bana diya jata hai (class load hote hi)
Ex - 
class Singleton {
    private static final Singleton instance = new Singleton();

    private Singleton() { }

    public static Singleton getInstance() {
        return instance;
    }
}

  1.2 Lazy Initialization (On-Demand)
       👉 Object tab banta hai jab first time zarurat ho
Ex - 
class Singleton {
    private static Singleton instance;

    private Singleton() { }

    public static Singleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            instance = new Singleton();
        }
        return instance;
    }
}

  1.3 Double-Checked Locking (Best Practical)
Ex - 
class Singleton {
    private static volatile Singleton instance;

    private Singleton() { }

    public static Singleton getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            synchronized (Singleton.class) {
                if (instance == null) {
                    instance = new Singleton();
                }
            }
        }
        return instance;
    }
}

1.4 Enum Singleton (Most Secure 🔥)
Ex - 
enum Singleton {
    INSTANCE;

    public void show() {
        System.out.println("Hello Singleton");
    }
}
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        // Access enum singleton
        Singleton singleton = Singleton.INSTANCE;

        singleton.show();   // method call  / or direct way Singleton.INSTANCE.show();
    }
}


